{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}
[[File:1940 Field Marshal Ceremony.gif|right|thumb|300px|Hitler posing with his field marshals at the ceremony]]

The '''1940 Field Marshal Ceremony''' refers to a promotion ceremony held at the [[Kroll Opera House]] in [[Berlin]] in which [[Adolf Hitler]] promoted twelve [[general]]s to the rank of ''[[Generalfeldmarschall]]'' ("[[field marshal]]") on 19 July 1940. It was the first occasion in [[World War II]] that Hitler appointed field marshals due to military achievements.

The prestigious rank of field marshal had been banned after the [[First World War]]. As part of the [[German re-armament|Nazi expansion of the military]], the rank was revived. Hitler promoted twelve selected generals to field marshal during the ceremony in Berlin for their role in the swift victory over [[France]] and the [[Low Countries]] and to raise morale. The ceremony highlighted the power and prestige of the [[Wehrmacht]]; France was considered to have had [[Military history of France during World War II|the strongest army in Europe]], yet had been humiliatingly defeated in just six weeks.

The ceremony was the first time Hitler appointed field marshals due to military achievements and was celebrated like no other promotion ceremony of the war.

==Field marshal==
{{main|Generalfeldmarschall}}
After World War I, the prestigious and respected rank of field marshal was banned, alongside other [[Treaty of Versailles|military restrictions]] imposed on the newly formed [[Weimar Republic]]. After Hitler and Nazis came to national power in January 1933, they began an enormous expansion of the military; it was part of Hitler's desire to restore the army's power and prestige.{{sfn|Weinberg|1970|pp=26–27}} In 1936, he revived the rank of field marshal. It was the highest and most prestigious military rank in Germany, originally only for the use of the [[Minister of War]] and [[Commander-in-Chief]] of the Army.{{sfn|Hakim|1995|pp=100–104}} The traditional attribute distinguishing a German field marshal was an ornately decorated baton.{{sfn|Alford|2003|pp=66–67}} More tangible benefits included a yearly salary of 36,000 ''[[Reichsmarks]]'' and all earnings being exempt from income tax.{{sfn|Snyder|1994|p=111}}

== Ceremony ==
{{also|Battle of France}}
Flushed with enthusiasm by the swift defeat of the French army, considered to have been the strongest in Europe,{{sfn|Rees|2012}} and the Low Countries in June 1940, Hitler wanted to mark the occasion with a grand promotion ceremony.{{sfn|Mitcham|2009|p=24}} He also hoped the promotions would strengthen his influence over the traditional [[German General Staff]].{{sfn|Snyder|1994|pp=111–112}} The twelve generals chosen for promotion, who all had played an important role in the victory, were:

* Colonel General [[Walther von Brauchitsch]]{{sfn|Snyder|1994|p=112}}
* Colonel General [[Fedor von Bock]]{{sfn|Turney|1971|p=6}}
* General [[Albert Kesselring]]{{sfn|Kesselring|1970|p=55}}
* Colonel General [[Wilhelm Keitel]]{{sfn|Sandler|2002|p=455}}
* Colonel General [[Günther von Kluge]]{{sfn|Moczarski|1981|pp=226–234}}
* Colonel General [[Wilhelm von Leeb]]{{sfn|Shirer|1960|p=647}}
* Colonel General [[Wilhelm List]]{{sfn|Williamson|2006|p=28}}
* Colonel General [[Erhard Milch]]{{sfn|Snyder|1994|p=229}}
* Colonel General [[Walther von Reichenau]]{{sfn|Biesinger|2006|p=619}}
* Colonel General [[Gerd von Rundstedt]]{{sfn|Mackenzie|2014|p=17}}
* General [[Hugo Sperrle]]{{sfn|Williamson|2006|p=46}}
* Colonel General [[Erwin von Witzleben]]{{sfn|Mitcham|2009a|pp=1–2}}

Additionally, Field Marshal [[Hermann Göring]], head of the Luftwaffe, was promoted to the specially-created rank of Reich Marshal of the Greater German Reich, a newly created rank that not only made Göring the senior officer of the military, but also confirmed an earlier Hitler decree naming Göring his successor. This was the only award of this rank during the Nazi era, and it was abolished after the fall of the Nazi regime. <ref>''Rise and Fall of the Third Reich'', by William L. Shirer. Published 1960.</ref> {{sfn|Manvell|2011|p=245}}[[File:German field marshals baton.gif|thumb|300px|left|A decorated baton became the trademark of a German field marshal.]]

On 19 July 1940, Hitler summoned the generals to a ceremony in Berlin's [[Kroll Opera House]] (which housed the [[Reichstag (Nazi Germany)|Reichstag]] after the [[Reichstag fire]]).{{sfn|Deighton|2008|pp=7–9}}{{sfn|Evans|2008|pp=122–123}}{{sfn|Mitcham|2009|p=24}} After a speech regarding a peace proposal directed at Britain, Hitler personally rewarded his generals with their expensively decorated batons,{{sfn|Deighton|2008|pp=7–9}}{{sfn|Alford|2003|pp=66–67}} and thanked them for their contributions to the victory.{{sfn|Dear|Foot|2005|p=322}}{{sfn|Ellis|1993|p=94}}{{efn|name=Göring rank}}

The 1940 Field Marshal Ceremony was the first occasion Hitler appointed field marshals due to military achievements and was celebrated like no other promotion ceremony in Germany.{{sfn|Mitcham|2009|p=24}}{{sfn|Tague|2011|p=150}} The remaining five years of the war saw an additional [[List of German field marshals#Nazi Germany|twelve promotions]], most of which were without ceremony, such as [[Friedrich Paulus]]'s promotion, which was conferred over the radio by Hitler.{{sfn|Beevor|1998|p=381}}{{sfn|Snyder|1994|p=112}}{{efn
| name = Paulus incident
| 1=In deciding to promote Paulus during the [[Battle of Stalingrad]], Hitler noted that there was no known record of a [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussian]] or German field marshal ever having surrendered. The implication was clear: Paulus was to commit suicide. If Paulus surrendered, Hitler implied he would shame Germany's military history. Paulus, nevertheless, surrendered to Soviet forces on 31 January 1943, the day after he was promoted.{{sfn|Snyder|1994|p=112}}
}}

==Aftermath==
{{also|20 July plot}}
All of the generals promoted would go on to achieve further success in their careers during the early years of victory which the German military obtained in the Second World War. Brauchitsch, Bock, Kesselring, Keitel, Leeb, List, Reichenau, Rundstedt, and Göring would all play decisive and important roles in the German-led [[Operation Barbarossa|Axis invasion of the Soviet Union]] in 1941.{{sfn|Grazhdan|2011}} Sperrle spent the rest of the war in semi-retirement, based with his unit in France.{{sfn|Williamson|2006|p=46}} Milch was transferred to the production department and was responsible for aircraft production until the end of the war. In 1943, after a series of German defeats on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]], and the Allied invasion of [[Italy]], the German military lost all initiative.{{sfn|Rees|2012}} Hitler's leadership became increasingly disconnected from reality as the war turned against Germany, with the military's defensive strategies often hindered by his slow decision making and frequent directives to hold untenable positions.{{sfn|Rees|2012}} His response to the worsening war situation was to unceremoniously sack general after general, a routine which ultimately affected the field marshals promoted at the ceremony.{{sfn|Rees|2012}} [[Erwin von Witzleben]] and [[Günther von Kluge]] were both involved in the [[20 July Plot]] to assassinate Hitler. After it became clear that the assassination attempt had failed, Kluge committed suicide by taking [[cyanide|cyanide poison]] on 17 August 1944.{{sfn|Moczarski|1981|pp=226–234}} Witzleben, who was to become Commander-in-Chief of the [[Wehrmacht]] if the attempt had succeeded, was arrested and sentenced to death; the execution was carried out on 8 August 1944.{{sfn|Snyder|1994|p=382}}

