[[Category:War crimes by war]]
[[Category:World War II|War Crimes]]

'''Evacuation in the Soviet Union''' is the evacuation of people and industry after the [[Operation Barbarossa|German invasion in 1941]]. According to Rebeca Marley over sixteen million Soviet civilians were evacuted.<ref>[http://www.cornellpress.cornell.edu/book/?GCOI=80140100797910 To the Tashkent Station, Evacuation and Survival in the Soviet Union at War]</ref><ref>[https://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=32096 Reviewed by Nicholas Ganson]</ref> According to [[Walter S. Dunn]] 1,523 large factories were moved by the end of 1941.<ref>"The Soviet economy and the Red Army, 1930-1945" by Walter S. Dunn, page 34</ref> Prisoners were evacuated, many of them [[NKVD prisoner massacres|massacred]]. [[Lenin's Mausoleum|Lenin's body]] was moved to [[Tyumen]]. Part of [[Hermitage Museum]] collection was evacuated to [[Yekaterinburg|Sverdlovsk]]. [[Samara, Russia|Kuybyshev]] was the alternative capital of the Soviet Union 1941-1943. [[Novosibirsk]] received more than 140,000 refugees and many factories.
==Evacuation of Industry== Due to [[Operation Barbarossa|the speed of the inital German advance,]] factories were in danger not only because of the threat of being lost to the Germans, but the general collapse of the civilian economy along with this loss of territorry, leading to a lack of supplies and as such, productivity.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harrison|first1=Mark|title=The Soviet Defense Industry Complex in World War II|url=https://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/soc/economics/staff/mharrison/public/dfc1994postprint.pdf|website=The University of Warwick|publisher=University of Tokyo Press|accessdate=10 January 2017|ref=https://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/soc/economics/staff/mharrison/public/dfc1994postprint.pdf|pages=7-8|date=March 22, 1993}}</ref> ==Notes and references== {{reflist|2}}
